r 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n|}\n\n===Testing===\nThe monitoring and testing of COVID-19 in South Carolina per the Department of Health and Environmental Control is as follows:<ref name=\"DHECcount\"/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Type !! Number\n|-\n|Negative tests || 5,033\n|-\n|Positive tests || 1,293\n|}\n\n==Impact on sports==\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> This affected South Carolina especially, as the [[Bon Secours Wellness Arena]] in [[Greenville, South Carolina|Greenville]] was set to host first and second-round games in the women's tournament.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fair |first1=Jim |title=Greenville selected to host NCAA men and women basketball tournaments |url=http://greertoday.com/greer-sc/greenville-selected-to-host-ncaa-men-and-women-basketball-tournaments/2017/04/18/ |website=GreerToday.com |accessdate=23 March 2020 |date=18 April 2017}}</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://scdhec.gov/infectious-diseases/viruses/coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19 Coronavirus information] from the [[South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|South Carolina]]\n[[Category:2020 in South Carolina|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Health in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "FranksValli", "label": "safe", "comment": "Statistics: fix link to Allendale county", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Carolina"}
{"title_page": "Me and Bobby McGee", "text_new": "{{short description|Song by Kris Kristofferson and Fred Foster}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{for|the album entitled ''Me and Bobby McGee''|Kristofferson (album)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Me and Bobby McGee\n| cover      = Me and Bobby McGee - Roger Miller.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Roger Miller]]\n| album      = Roger Miller 1970\n| released   = July 1969\n| format     = [[7\"]]\n| recorded   = May 16, 1969\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 4:02\n| label      = [[Smash Records|Smash]] S-2230\n| writer     = [[Kris Kristofferson]]<br>[[Fred Foster]]\n| producer   = [[Jerry Kennedy]]\n| prev_title = Vance\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = Where Have All the Average People Gone\n| next_year  = 1969\n}}\n\"'''Me and Bobby McGee'''\" is a song written by American singer-songwriter [[Kris Kristofferson]] and originally performed by [[Roger Miller]]. Fred Foster shares the writing credit, as Kristofferson intended.  A posthumously released version by [[Janis Joplin]] topped the [[Billboard Hot 100|U.S. singles chart]] in 1971,   making the song the second posthumously released No. 1 single in [[United States|U.S.]] chart history after \"[[(Sittin' On) The Dock of the Bay]]\" by [[Otis Redding]]. Jerry Lee Lewis also released a version reaching number 1 on the country charts in 1971. ''Billboard'' ranked Joplin's version as the [[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1971|No. 11 song for 1971]].\n\nOther recordings of the song include those by [[Waylon Jennings]], [[Grateful Dead]], [[Loretta Lynn]], Kristofferson himself,<ref name=\"Hutchinson\">{{cite web |author= Lydia Hutchinson |title= Kris Kristofferson's \"Me and Bobby McGee\" |url=http://performingsongwriter.com/kris-kristofferson-bobby-mcgee/ |date= June 22, 2013 |access-date= }}</ref> [[Kenny Rogers and The First Edition]], [[Gordon Lightfoot]], [[Dolly Parton]], [[Miranda Lambert]], [[Olivia Newton-John]],  [[Vicki Britton]] and [[Johnny Cash]].\n\n==History==\nThe suggestion for the title came from producer and Monument Records founder Fred Foster.<ref name=\"Hutchinson\"/> \nKristofferson explained that in the song he was trying to convey the despair of the last scene of [[Frederico Fellini]]\u2019s \u2018\u2019[[La Strada]]\u2019\u2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wideopencountry.com/me-and-bobby-mcgee-story-behind-the-song/ |title='Me and Bobby McGee': The Story Behind the Song|website=Wide Open Country|date=|accessdate=September 23, 2019|first=Courtney|last=Campbell}}</ref>\n\n==Narrative==\nThe song is the story of two drifters, the narrator and Bobby McGee.  The couple [[Hitchhiking|hitch a ride]] from a truck driver and sing as they drive through the [[American South]].  They visit California and then part ways, with the song's narrator expressing sadness afterwards. Due to the singer's name never being mentioned and the name \"Bobby\" being easily identifiable to both sexes, the song has been recorded by both male and female singers with only minor changes needed to the lyrical content.\n\n==Recordings and notable performances==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Me and Bobby McGee\n| cover      = Me_and_Bobby_McGee_-_Janis_Joplin.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Janis Joplin]]\n| album      = [[Pearl (Janis Joplin album)|Pearl]]\n| B-side     = Half Moon\n| released   = January 12, 1971<ref>https://www.45cat.com/record/445314us</ref>\n| format     =\n| recorded   = September 5 \u2013 October 1, 1970\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Blues rock]], [[country rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=4|s=33}}\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     = [[Kris Kristofferson]], [[Fred Foster]]\n| producer   = [[Paul A. Rothchild]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nRoger Miller was the first artist to record the song and it appeared at No. 12 on the U.S. country chart in 1969.<ref>Whitburn, Joel, Joel Whitburn\u2019s Top Country Songs: 1944-2005, Billboard, Record Research Inc., Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin  2005 p. 252</ref>  [[Gordon Lightfoot]]'s version hit No. 13 on the pop music chart and No. 1 country music chart in his native country of Canada in 1970.  The song was included on a [[Statler Brothers]] album but was not released as a single.\n\n[[Kenny Rogers and The First Edition]] recorded the song (with Rogers on lead vocals) and released it on their album ''[[Ruby, Don't Take Your Love To Town]]'' in 1969.\n\nKristofferson recorded his own version of the song on his debut album ''[[Kristofferson (album)|Kristofferson]]'' in 1970. Later that year, his version of the song appeared in [[Monte Hellman]]'s [[psychedelic film|psychedelic]] [[road movie]] ''[[Two-Lane Blacktop]]''. Kristofferson also appears briefly singing the song in the 1971 [[Dennis Hopper]] film ''[[The Last Movie]]''.\n\nJoplin recorded the song for inclusion on her ''[[Pearl (Janis Joplin album)|Pearl]]'' album only a few days before her death in October 1970. Kristofferson had sung the song for her, and singer [[Bob Neuwirth]] taught it to her. Kristofferson did not know she had recorded it until after her death. The first time he heard her recording of it was the day after she died.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hawke |first=Ethan |authorlink=Ethan Hawke |title=The Last Outlaw Poet |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=1076 |page=57 |date=April 16, 2009 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/27113898/the_last_outlaw_poet |accessdate=April 10, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410055914/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/27113898/the_last_outlaw_poet |archivedate=April 10, 2009 }}</ref>  Joplin's version topped the charts to become her only number one single and in 2004, her version of this song was ranked No. 148 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of [[the 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].\n\n==Chart performance==\n====Weekly singles charts====\n===Roger Miller version===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1969)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot Country Singles<ref>{{cite book |title= The Billboard Book Of Top 40 Country Hits: 1944-2006, Second edition|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=232}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Bubbling Under Hot 100<ref>Joel Whitburn's Bubbling Under the Billboard Hot 100 1959-2004</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian ''RPM'' Country Tracks\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|}\n===Gordon Lightfoot version===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1970)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Canada ''RPM'' Country Tracks\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio|Springbok]])<ref>{{cite web|title=SA Charts 1965\u2013March 1989|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(L).html|date=13 August 1971|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|}\n\n===Janis Joplin version===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1971)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australia [[Kent Music Report|KMR]] <ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= [[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970-1992]] |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], N.S.W. |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canada [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'']] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.5182&URLjpg=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/028020/f4/nlc008388.5182.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.5182|title=Image : RPM Weekly|first=Library and Archives|last=Canada|date=July 17, 2013|publisher=Bac-lac.gc.ca|accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|New Zealand <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20listener&qartistid=1374#n_view_location |title=flavour of new zealand - search listener |website=Flavourofnz.co.nz |date= |accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] <ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19710327.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=June 4, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624211527/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19710327.html |archivedate=June 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|}\n===Jerry Lee Lewis version===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1971-72)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.5302&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.5302.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.5302|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1972-01-22 |accessdate=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|50\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955\u20131990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|40\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|39\n|-\n|U.S. [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>[http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/70s_files/19720115.html Cash Box Top 100 Singles, January 15, 1972]</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|63\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1971)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Australia <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ |title=Australian Chart Book |website=Austchartbook.com.au |accessdate=October 2, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305064644/http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ |archivedate=March 5, 2016 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|17\n|-\n|Canada <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.7590&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=mhe12pta2k83e08udtq66ot062|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada|work=collectionscanada.gc.ca}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|79\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1971.htm |title=Top 100 Hits of 1971/Top 100 Songs of 1971 |website=Musicoutfitters.com |date= |accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|-\n|U.S. ''Cash Box'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1971YESP.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 30, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626162215/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1971YESP.html |archivedate=June 26, 2015 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|29\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Selected list of recorded versions==\n*1969 [[Roger Miller]] - album ''Roger Miller''\n*1969 [[The Stonemans]] - album [[Ernest_Stoneman#The_Stonemans_discography|''Dawn of the Stonemans' Age'']]\n*1969 [[Kenny Rogers & The First Edition]] - album ''[[Ruby, Don't Take Your Love to Town (album)|Ruby, Don't Take Your Love to Town]]''\n*1970 [[Charley Pride]] - album ''[[Just Plain Charley]]''\n*1970 [[Ramblin' Jack Elliott]] - album ''[[Bull Durham Sacks & Railroad Tracks]]''\n*1970 [[The Statler Brothers]] - album ''[[Bed of Rose's (album)|Bed of Rose's]]''\n*1970 [[Gordon Lightfoot]] - album ''[[Sit Down Young Stranger]]''\n*1970 [[Kris Kristofferson]] - album ''[[Kristofferson (album)|Kristofferson]]''  (Kristofferson's version also appears in the film ''[[Two-Lane Blacktop]]'')\n*1970 [[Bill Haley & His Comets]] - album ''Rock Around the Country''. (According to the biography ''Bill Haley'' by [[John Swenson]], Kristofferson gave Haley's version his seal of approval.)\n*1970 [[Sam the Sham|Sam The Sham]] - single \"Me And Bobby McGee/Key To The Highway\" (Atlantic #2757)\n*1971 [[John Mogensen]] as \"Carsten Levin\" <sub>Danish</sub> - single/ featured on album ''John'' (1973)\n*1971 [[Janis Joplin]] U.S. number-one single: parent album ''[[Pearl (Janis Joplin album)|Pearl]]'' \n*1971 & 1972 [[Jerry Lee Lewis]] - album ''The Killer Rocks On''/ [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] of \"Would You Take Another Chance on Me\"\n*1971 [[Dottie West]] - album ''Have You Heard...''\n*1971 [[Grateful Dead]] - album ''[[Skull & Roses]]'', and numerous other live recordings\n*1971 [[Loretta Lynn]] - album ''[[I Wanna Be Free (Loretta Lynn album)|I Wanna Be Free]]''\n*1971 [[Lalla Hansson]] as \"Anna & mej\" <sub>Swedish</sub> - album ''[[Upp till Ragvaldstr\u00e4sk]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Lalla-Hansson-Anna-Mej/release/1839438 |title=Lalla Hansson - Anna & Mej (Vinyl) |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://smdb.kb.se/catalog/id/001478826 |title=Upp till Ragvaldstr\u00e4sk! &#124; Svensk mediedatabas |website=SMDB.kb.se |date= |accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref> scoring a [[Tio i topp]] hit.\n*1972 [[Johnny Cash]] - album ''[[P\u00e5 \u00d6ster\u00e5ker]]''\n*1972 [[Charlie McCoy]] - album ''Charlie McCoy''\n*1972 [[Jeannie C. Riley]]  - album ''Give Myself a Party''\n*1973 [[Waylon Jennings]] - album ''[[Lonesome, On'ry and Mean]]''\n*1973 [[Chet Atkins]] - album ''[[Alone (Chet Atkins album)|Alone]]''\n*1973 [[Thelma Houston]] - album ''[[Thelma Houston (1972)|Thelma Houston]]''\n*1973 [[Olivia Newton-John]] - album ''[[Let Me Be There (album)|Let Me Be There]]''\n*1974 [[Lonnie Donegan]] - album ''Lonnie Donegan Meets Leinemann''\n*1974 [[Cornelis Vreeswijk]] as \"Jag och Bosse Lid\u00e9n\" <sub>Swedish</sub> - album ''Getinghonung''\n*1979 [[Gianna Nannini]] as \"Io e Bobby McGee\" <sub>Italian</sub> - album ''[[California (Gianna Nannini album)|California]]''\n*1984 [[Joan Baez]] - album ''[[Live Europe '83]]'' album: Baez also performed the song with the [[Boston Pops]] in 1985.\n*1990 [[The Highwaymen (country supergroup)|The Highwaymen]] - Live: American Outlaws\n*1994 [[Blind Melon]] records the song in the studio during a session in The Netherlands, appears on their B-sides collection.\n*1994 [[Melissa Etheridge]] - album ''Acoustic''\n*1997 [[Loquillo (singer)|Loquillo]] - album ''Compa\u00f1eros de viaje''\n*1999 [[LeAnn Rimes]] - album ''[[LeAnn Rimes (album)|LeAnn Rimes]]''\n*1999 [[Barb Jungr]] - album ''[[Bare (Barb Jungr album)|Bare]]''\n*2002 [[Anne Murray]] - album ''[[Country Croonin']]''\n*2002 [[Jennifer Love Hewitt]] - album ''[[Bare Naked]]''\n*2002 [[Waterloo & Robinson]] as \"Ich und BobbyMcGee\" <sub>German</sub> - album ''Marianne''\n*2003 [[Jerry Jeff Walker]] - album ''Too Old To Change''\n*2004 [[Pink (singer)|Pink]] - album ''Live in Europe''\n*2005 [[Dolly Parton]] - album ''[[Those Were The Days (Dolly Parton album)|Those Were The Days]]'' \n*2005 [[Arlo Guthrie]] - album ''Live In Sydney''\n*2006 [[Dale Ann Bradley]] - album ''Catch Tomorrow''\n*2007 Angela Kalule on the soundtrack of [[The Last King of Scotland (film)|''The Last King of Scotland'']]\n*2007 [[Caroline af Ugglas]] - album ''Joplin p\u00e5 Svenska''\n*2008 [[Amanda Strydom]] - album ''kerse teen die donker''\n*2010 [[Crystal Bowersox]] on ''[[American Idol]]'' [[iTunes]] release of studio version from Top 11 week, and Final 2 week, of [[American Idol (season 9)|season 9]]\n*2016 [[Matt Doyle (actor)|Matt Doyle]] - album ''Uncontrolled''\n\n;Other artists\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*[[Roy Clark]]\n*[[John Doe (musician)|John Doe]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/John+Doe/_/Me+and+Bobby+McGee |title=John Doe \u2014 Me and Bobby McGee |website=Last.fm |date= |accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Dave Dudley]]\n*[[Bobbie Gentry]]\n*[[Taylor Horn]]\n*[[Impotent Sea Snakes]]\n*[[Aaron Lewis (musician)|Aaron Lewis]]\n*[[Reba McEntire]]\n*[[Brian McKnight]]\n*[[Willie Nelson]]\n*[[Amanda Overmyer]]\n*[[Buck Owens]]\n*[[Celinda Pink]]\n*[[The Platters]]\n*[[Hank Snow]]\n*[[Bobby Bare]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://archive.is/20110708122437/http://www.cartoonbank.com/1991/freedoms-just-another-word-for-nothin-left-to-lose-judge/invt/111321/ ''New Yorker'' cartoon quoting the song]\n* [http://www.secondhandsongs.com/song/29796 A SecondHandSongs list of selected artists who covered \"Me and Bobby McGee\"]\n* {{MetroLyrics song|roger-miller|me-and-bobby-mcgee}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CJr3Fkv81bU FILM:ACOUSTIC - Kris Kristofferson performs \"Me and Bobby McGee\" and relates ''La Strada''] by [http://www.modernschooloffilm.com/ The Modern School of Film] at [https://web.archive.org/web/20140505182011/https://www.arclightcinemas.com/en/news/arcp-msf ArcLight Presents...]\n*[http://www.historybyday.com/pop-culture/the-epic-story-behind-janis-joplin-and-me-and-bobby-mcgee/?view-all The Epic Story Behind Janis Joplin\u2019s \u201cMe and Bobby McGee\u201d] at History by Day\n\n{{Roger Miller}}\n{{Bill Haley & His Comets}}\n{{Janis Joplin}}\n{{Jerry Lee Lewis}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Me And Bobby Mcgee}}\n[[Category:1969 singles]]\n[[Category:1971 singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Taylor Horn songs]]\n[[Category:Joan Baez songs]]\n[[Category:Grateful Dead songs]]\n[[Category:Bill Haley songs]]\n[[Category:Janis Joplin songs]]\n[[Category:Kris Kristofferson songs]]\n[[Category:Gordon Lightfoot songs]]\n[[Category:Roger Miller songs]]\n[[Category:Jerry Lee Lewis songs]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Australia]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kris Kristofferson]]\n[[Category:RPM Country Tracks number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n[[Category:1969 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Jerry Kennedy]]\n[[Category:Songs about trains]]\n[[Category:Lalla Hansson songs]]\n[[Category:Songs released posthumously]]\n[[Category:BNA Records singles]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n[[Category:Smash Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Song by Kris Kristofferson and Fred Foster}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{for|the album entitled ''Me and Bobby McGee''|Kristofferson (album)}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Me and Bobby McGee\n| cover      = Me and Bobby McGee - Roger Miller.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Roger Miller]]\n| album      = Roger Miller 1970\n| released   = July 1969\n| format     = [[7\"]]\n| recorded   = May 16, 1969\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = 4:02\n| label      = [[Smash Records|Smash]] S-2230\n| writer     = [[Kris Kristofferson]]<br>[[Fred Foster]]\n| producer   = [[Jerry Kennedy]]\n| prev_title = Vance\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = Where Have All the Average People Gone\n| next_year  = 1969\n}}\n\"'''Me and Bobby McGee'''\" is a song written by American singer-songwriter [[Kris Kristofferson]] and originally performed by [[Roger Miller]]. Fred Foster shares the writing credit, as Kristofferson intended.  A posthumously released version by [[Janis Joplin]] topped the [[Billboard Hot 100|U.S. singles chart]] in 1971,   making the song the second posthumously released No. 1 single in [[United States|U.S.]] chart history after \"[[(Sittin' On) The Dock of the Bay]]\" by [[Otis Redding]]. Jerry Lee Lewis also released a version reaching number 1 on the country charts in 1971. ''Billboard'' ranked Joplin's version as the [[Billboard Year-End Hot 100 singles of 1971|No. 11 song for 1971]].\n\nOther recordings of the song include those by [[Waylon Jennings]], [[Grateful Dead]], [[Loretta Lynn]], Kristofferson himself,<ref name=\"Hutchinson\">{{cite web |author= Lydia Hutchinson |title= Kris Kristofferson's \"Me and Bobby McGee\" |url=http://performingsongwriter.com/kris-kristofferson-bobby-mcgee/ |date= June 22, 2013 |access-date= }}</ref> [[Kenny Rogers and The First Edition]], [[Gordon Lightfoot]], [[Dolly Parton]], [[Miranda Lambert]], [[Olivia Newton-John]],  [[Vicki Britton]] and [[Johnny Cash]].\n\n==History==\nThe suggestion for the title came from producer and Monument Records founder Fred Foster.<ref name=\"Hutchinson\"/> \nKristofferson explained that in the song he was trying to convey the despair of the last scene of [[Frederico Fellini]]\u2019s \u2018\u2019[[La Strada]]\u2019\u2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wideopencountry.com/me-and-bobby-mcgee-story-behind-the-song/ |title='Me and Bobby McGee': The Story Behind the Song|website=Wide Open Country|date=|accessdate=September 23, 2019|first=Courtney|last=Campbell}}</ref>\n\n==Narrative==\nThe song is the story of two drifters, the narrator and Bobby McGee.  The couple [[Hitchhiking|hitch a ride]] from a truck driver and sing as they drive through the [[American south]].  They visit California and then part ways, with the song's narrator expressing sadness afterwards. Due to the singer's name never being mentioned and the name \"Bobby\" being easily identifiable to both sexes, the song has been recorded by both male and female singers with only minor changes needed to the lyrical content.\n\n==Recordings and notable performances==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Me and Bobby McGee\n| cover      = Me_and_Bobby_McGee_-_Janis_Joplin.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Janis Joplin]]\n| album      = [[Pearl (Janis Joplin album)|Pearl]]\n| B-side     = Half Moon\n| released   = January 12, 1971<ref>https://www.45cat.com/record/445314us</ref>\n| format     =\n| recorded   = September 5 \u2013 October 1, 1970\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Blues rock]], [[country rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=4|s=33}}\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     = [[Kris Kristofferson]], [[Fred Foster]]\n| producer   = [[Paul A. Rothchild]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nRoger Miller was the first artist to record the song and it appeared at No. 12 on the U.S. country chart in 1969.<ref>Whitburn, Joel, Joel Whitburn\u2019s Top Country Songs: 1944-2005, Billboard, Record Research Inc., Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin  2005 p. 252</ref>  [[Gordon Lightfoot]]'s version hit No. 13 on the pop music chart and No. 1 country music chart in his native country of Canada in 1970.  The song was included on a [[Statler Brothers]] album but was not released as a single.\n\n[[Kenny Rogers and The First Edition]] recorded the song (with Rogers on lead vocals) and released it on their album ''[[Ruby, Don't Take Your Love To Town]]'' in 1969.\n\nKristofferson recorded his own version of the song on his debut album ''[[Kristofferson (album)|Kristofferson]]'' in 1970. Later that year, his version of the song appeared in [[Monte Hellman]]'s [[psychedelic film|psychedelic]] [[road movie]] ''[[Two-Lane Blacktop]]''. Kristofferson also appears briefly singing the song in the 1971 [[Dennis Hopper]] film ''[[The Last Movie]]''.\n\nJoplin recorded the song for inclusion on her ''[[Pearl (Janis Joplin album)|Pearl]]'' album only a few days before her death in October 1970. Kristofferson had sung the song for her, and singer [[Bob Neuwirth]] taught it to her. Kristofferson did not know she had recorded it until after her death. The first time he heard her recording of it was the day after she died.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hawke |first=Ethan |authorlink=Ethan Hawke |title=The Last Outlaw Poet |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=1076 |page=57 |date=April 16, 2009 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/27113898/the_last_outlaw_poet |accessdate=April 10, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410055914/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/27113898/the_last_outlaw_poet |archivedate=April 10, 2009 }}</ref>  Joplin's version topped the charts to become her only number one single and in 2004, her version of this song was ranked No. 148 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of [[the 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].\n\n==Chart performance==\n====Weekly singles charts====\n===Roger Miller version===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1969)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot Country Singles<ref>{{cite book |title= The Billboard Book Of Top 40 Country Hits: 1944-2006, Second edition|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=232}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Bubbling Under Hot 100<ref>Joel Whitburn's Bubbling Under the Billboard Hot 100 1959-2004</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|22\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian ''RPM'' Country Tracks\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|}\n===Gordon Lightfoot version===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1970)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Canada ''RPM'' Country Tracks\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n|South Africa ([[Springbok Radio|Springbok]])<ref>{{cite web|title=SA Charts 1965\u2013March 1989|url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(L).html|date=13 August 1971|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|}\n\n===Janis Joplin version===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1971)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Australia [[Kent Music Report|KMR]] <ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= [[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970-1992]] |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], N.S.W. |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canada [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'']] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.5182&URLjpg=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/028020/f4/nlc008388.5182.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.5182|title=Image : RPM Weekly|first=Library and Archives|last=Canada|date=July 17, 2013|publisher=Bac-lac.gc.ca|accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|New Zealand <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20listener&qartistid=1374#n_view_location |title=flavour of new zealand - search listener |website=Flavourofnz.co.nz |date= |accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]] <ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19710327.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=June 4, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624211527/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19710327.html |archivedate=June 24, 2016 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|